{
  "text": "Several studies in CKD patients have shown that circulating FGF23, a hormone involved in phosphorous and vitamin D homeostasis, predicts adverse outcome [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Among patients with CKD stages 2-4, circulating FGF-23 is significantly associated with cardiovascular outcomes [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Guti\u00e9rrez et al. showed that rising FGF23 levels in patients beginning HD (CKD 5D) are independently associated with high mortality [CITATION_8] . Furthermore, a study with animal data showed that FGF23 induces left ventricular hypertrophy via FGF receptor-dependent activation [CITATION_9] . Our data, however, showed that serum FGF23 did not predict cardiovascular disease and mortality. Unlike previous reports, we focused on long-term HD patients (mean HD period 6.7 \u00b1 5.4 years) who have little urine volume. FGF23 increases urinary phosphorus excretion and inhibits activation of vitamin D in the renal proximal tubule [CITATION_10] , but these physiological effects of FGF23 on renal function may not be exerted in ESRD patients with little urine volume. In other words, the function and regulation of FGF23 in patients with deteriorated renal function are unknown. We speculate that the absence of correlation between FGF23 and clinical outcomes in our study may be a unique feature in patients with long-term maintained HD.",
  "correct_citation": {
